<h3 id="getting-started">Getting Started</h3>

<p>If you want to get up and running quickly with i3move,
refer to the manual.
<a href="https://dmbuce.github.io/i3b/i3move.html#EXAMPLES">The examples section</a>
near the bottom shows how to generate a default config and bind some keys using i3.
Thatâ€™s really all you need to get started.</p>

<p>However, there is a lot going on in the default config.
If you open it up with a text editor, you may find yourself wondering things like:
What the heck does <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">--inside-distance w</code> mean?
And <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">--small-distance =</code>?</p>

<p>The various options interact with each other
in a lot of ways to drive i3moveâ€™s default behavior,
so rather than try to explain everything all at once,
letâ€™s start with a simplified example
and work our way towards a more complicated config.</p>

<p>If you havenâ€™t already, you should install i3move.
Arch users can get it by installing the
<a href="https://aur.archlinux.org/packages/i3b">AURâ€™s i3b package</a>,
and on other distros you can download the script,
drop it in your <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">$PATH</code>, and make it executable.</p>

